Spotify - Music Trends From 1956 to 2019¶

A data science project by Yufei Liu¶

Introduction¶

Spotify provides users with digital music, podcasts and video services that make it easy to listen to millions of songs and watch other content from creators around the world. Users can discover, manage and share more than 82 million songs and more than 4 million podcasts for free. Or, users can upgrade to Spotify Premium, which gives them access to exclusive music features, including improved sound quality and an on-demand, offline and ad-free music listening experience. Spotify is available on a range of devices, including computers, phones, tablets, speakers, TVs and cars, and with Spotify Connect you can easily transition from one device to another. Today, Spotify is the world's most popular audio streaming subscription service with 422 million subscribers in 183 markets, including 182 million subscribers.

I really like use Spotify, and I also like listening music to relax myself during the free time. Therefore, I want to do a project about Spotify. After searching a lot of dataset, I decided to analyze the most popular genre based on the different decade. In my project, I will use the dataset "Spotify - All Time Top 2000s Mega Dataset" which contains audio statistics of roughly from between 1956 to 2019 on Spotify and describes the qualities of the top 2000 songs on Spotify as of 2019. In this project, I will focus on the following questions: which genres were more popular coming through 1950s to 2000s? Which factor will affect the popularity of a song? I believe these questions can help the musicians to improve their music and know what most people like in each decade, and it can also helps people to get more information about music history.

Content Variables¶

  • Index: ID

  • Title: Name of the Track

  • Artist: Name of the Artist

  • Top Genre: Genre of the track

  • Year: Release Year of the track

  • Beats per Minute(BPM): The tempo of the song

  • Energy: The energy of a song - the higher the value, the more energtic song.

  • Danceability: The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.

  • Loudness: The higher the value, the louder the song.

  • Valence: The higher the value, the more positive mood for the song.

  • Length: The duration of the song.

  • Acoustic: The higher the value the more acoustic the song is.

  • Speechiness: The higher the value the more spoken words the song contains.

  • Popularity: The higher the value the more popular the song is.

Tidying and Modifying Data¶

After gaining a minimal understanding of the entire database, I try to clean up the data. I change the name of columns: Top Genre, Beats Per Minute (BPM), Loudness (dB), and Length (Duration). Because these names have spaces and parentheses, they may cause some problems in use. Also, I change the type of Title, Artist, Genre, Duration from Object to string for later use in data analysis.

In [160]:
# change the name of some columns
spotify.rename(columns={'Top Genre': 'Genre',
                        'Beats Per Minute (BPM)': 'BPM',
                        'Loudness (dB)': 'dB',
                        'Length (Duration)': 'Duration',
                        }, inplace=True)

There are currently 149 genre categories, but there are many duplicate and overly detailed branches, so here I have divided them into 68 categories, which will reduce the possibility of duplication of categories while analyzing the data.

In [162]:
# delete duplicate genre
# shorten the name of genre
new_genre = spotify['Genre'].copy()
while(max((new_genre.str.split(" ", 1)).str.len()) > 1):
  result = new_genre.str.split(" ",1)
  for i in range(len(result)):
      if (len(result[i]) > 1):
          result[i] = [result[i][1]]
  new_genre =  result.str.join('')
spotify['Genre'] = new_genre
spotify['Genre'].value_counts()

In [166]:
# seperate the data based on decade
sixties_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >1959) & (spotify.Year <1970)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]
seventies_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >1969) & (spotify.Year <1980)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]
eighties_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >1979) & (spotify.Year <1990)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]
nineties_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >1989) & (spotify.Year <2000)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]
thousands_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >1999) & (spotify.Year <2010)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]
tens_data = spotify[(spotify.Year >2009) & (spotify.Year <2020)][['Genre', 'Popularity']]

I first counted the distribution of all the songs on the list in each decade and the total number, and we can guess that there was a very rapid shift in the songs of the 1960s and 1970s, probably because ideas became more open or listening devices were developed. Then, I want to use violinplot to gain the general information of popularity over years and the popularity per song over years, because this kind of graph can give us the median and the probability of each part.

Resources:

How to use violinplot in python: https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.violinplot.html

In [173]:
# put the total popularity of each year into a new array
# the format is: (year, total popularity in this year)
# plot it in violinplot and analyze
total_data = []
total_data.append(('1960s', sixties_data.Popularity.sum()))
total_data.append(('1970s', seventies_data.Popularity.sum()))
total_data.append(('1980s', eighties_data.Popularity.sum()))
total_data.append(('1990s', nineties_data.Popularity.sum()))
total_data.append(('2000s', thousands_data.Popularity.sum()))
total_data.append(('2010s', tens_data.Popularity.sum()))
print(total_data)
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 8))
sns.violinplot(x=[x[1] for x in total_data])
plt.title('popularity by time period', fontweight = 'bold')
plt.xlabel('popularity')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.show()

Here, I use violinplot to show the popularity over time period, and the median is around 22000 in total each year, which is pretty high, and only 1960s is far from this number. Also, we can learn that the 2000s was the golden age of music, as the songs that ranked in the top 2000 were the most numerous and had the highest level of popularity at the same time.

I use heatmap because I can easily see the corraltion between two variables through the color.

Through this heatmap, we can see that speechless, energy, danceability and loudness have the greatest effect on popularity. However, we can not see a pretty clear correlation from the graph above. So, I multiply them together to form a new variable--possible factors. After that, I will try to find out the regression equation by the new variable.

In [186]:
# create a new variable with the multiplication of these four factors
# then find the slope and intercept
# draw it in the scatter plot
spotify['possible_factor'] = spotify['Energy'] * spotify['dB'] * spotify['Danceability'] * spotify['Valence']
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 8))
plt.scatter(spotify['possible_factor'], spotify['Popularity'], color = 'grey')
plt.title("possible_factor vs Popularity")
plt.ylim(0)
m,b = np.polyfit(spotify['possible_factor'], spotify['Popularity'], 1)
print(m)
plt.plot(spotify['possible_factor'], m*spotify['possible_factor'] + b, color = 'red')

-5.042261113618105e-07
Out[186]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f736d26a210>]

Through this image, we can see that there is a weak negative correlation between possible factors and popularity. So, we can probably conclude that the popularity of a song has a very weak relationship with its audio features like Danceability, Loudness, Danceability, Valence (Positivity).

Because the above combination brought less than ideal results, I recombined them according to the correlation between these four factors.

  • loudness & energy (74%)
  • valence & danceability (53%)
  • valence & energy (43%)

The highest correlation is loudness with 0.17, and it might be the most possible factor to affect the popularity.

Conclusion¶

Based on the above analysis, we can conclude that during the period from 1950s to 2000s, rock has been dominant and it not only has the largest circulation, but also the most popular. However, in the 2010s, pop took his place as the most popular genre. At the same time, we can also see that the genre of music has become more and more popular with the times, and there are many new genres being created.

In addition to analyzing the most popular genre, I also tried to understand the factors that influence popularity from these 2000 data. For all numeric data, I calculated their correlation with popularity, and the final conclusion was only weak positive correlation. Therefore, we can conclude that audio features don't have much effect on popularity, and a song's hotness is not specific to one reason.

In the article, I explain all the visualization methods I use and why I use this graph to present my results. I have also provided many links for my readers to learn more. I hope that this tutorial will not only give them an insight into the history of popular music, but also teach them how to analyze data well.
